column2: microbe

column3: a human microbiome that is located in a human cutaneous system

column2: bacterial microbiome

column2: microbiome

column2: host

column2: relative species abundance
column3: a quality of ecological community that refers to how common or rare a species is relative to other species in a defined location or community

column2: decreased organism quantity in acute disease patient compared with chronic disease control
column3: a quality with a depleted quantity of a type of organism (e.g., bacteria inside human gut) in a patient with an acute disease compared with a patient control with the same disease but at a chronic stage.

column2: decreased organism quantity compared with healthy controls

column2: increased organism quantity compared with healthy control
column3: a quality with an increased quantity of a type of organism (e.g., bacteria inside human gut) compared with control.

column2: beta diversity
column3: the ratio between regional and local species diversity

column2: alpha diversity
column3: the mean species diversity in sites or habitats at a local scale

column2: gamma diversity
column3: the total species diversity in a landscape

column2: relative abundance of microbe in host
column3: a relative species abundance that refers to the microbial species abundance in a host ecosystem

column2: descreased microbiome organism diversity
column3: a quality with an decreased microbiome organism dirversity in a host microbiome environment (e.g., gut).

column2: invisible to unaided eye
column3: a physical object quality that is inhered in a material entity that is too small to be viewed by the unaided eye.

column2: ph value
column3: a measurement datum that is a logarithmic scale used to specify the acidity or basicity of an aqueous solution. it is the negative of the base 10 logarithm of the activity of the hydrogen ion. at 25 c, solutions with a ph less than 7 are acidic and solutions with a ph greater than 7 are basic.
